The first one is easy to understand though.<p>parseInt takes two arguments: $thing_to_change and $radix; map iterates over an array and feeds it $value and $index. You&#x27;re getting parseInt(&quot;10&quot;, 0); parseInt(&quot;10&quot;, 1) and parseInt(&quot;10&quot;, 2);<p>The fix would be to partially apply parseInt with your defined radix;<p><pre><code>  var foo = [&quot;10&quot;, &quot;10&quot;, &quot;10&quot;];
  var base10 = function(val){ 
      return parseInt(val, 10); 
  };
  x = foo.map(base10)
  [10, 10, 10]</code></pre>

Some WTF moments in Javascript, courtesy of Gary Bernhardt:<p><pre><code>    var foo = [&quot;10&quot;, &quot;10&quot;, &quot;10&quot;];
    foo.map(parseInt);
    // Returns [ 10, NaN, 2 ]

    [] + [] // &quot;&quot;
    [] + {} // {}
    {} + [] // 0
    {} + {} // NaN

    var a = {};
    a[[]] = 2;
    alert(a[&quot;&quot;]); // alerts 2

    alert(Array(16).join(&quot;wat&quot; - 1) + &quot; Batman!&quot;);
</code></pre>
Press F12 and use the Console to verify these if you&#x27;re skeptical.
